# Styling and UI — Nuxt UI First

When creating or updating **pages**, **components**, or **layouts**, prefer **@nuxt/ui** components. Use the official component reference:

- **Component docs**: https://ui.nuxt.com/docs/components

## Use Nuxt UI Components

Before building custom UI, check whether a Nuxt UI component exists:

| Need | Prefer Nuxt UI | Notes |
|------|----------------|--------|
| Layout | App, Container, Main, Sidebar, Header, Footer | https://ui.nuxt.com/docs/components |
| Buttons, badges, cards | Button, Badge, Card, Avatar, Chip, Progress | Element group |
| Forms | Form, Input, Select, SelectMenu, Checkbox, Switch, Textarea | Form group; use UForm + Zod (see nuxt-ui-usage skill) |
| Data display | Table, Accordion, Carousel, Timeline, Empty | Data group |
| Navigation | Tabs, Breadcrumb, Pagination, Link | Navigation group |
| Modals, dropdowns, tooltips | Modal, Popover, DropdownMenu, Drawer, Toast, Tooltip | Overlay group |
| Date/time | Calendar, InputDate, InputTime | Element / Form |
| Dashboard | DashboardGroup, DashboardPanel, DashboardSidebar, DashboardToolbar | Dashboard group |

Use **Tailwind** (and project semantic utilities: `text-default`, `bg-elevated`, `border-muted`) for layout and spacing when using Nuxt UI. Project theme: `main` (primary), `secondary`, `neutral` — see `app/app.config.ts` and `.agent/skills/nuxt-ui-usage/SKILL.md`.

## When to Use Custom UI

- No suitable Nuxt UI component (e.g. highly custom calendar grid, domain-specific widget).
- Wrapping a Nuxt UI component in a project pattern (e.g. `components/Z/Modal/` wrappers).

For **custom-only** styling (no Tailwind), see `styling-legacy.mdc` — enable only when working on legacy or non–Nuxt UI code.

